{"notes": "Net read: modestly lower/flat nominal yields, a touch softer than my prior stance if I was carrying a neutral-to-up duration bias. The strongest, freshest signal is term_premium: 10y yield down sharply on the 21d window (-0.38pp), range position low (0.32), and this is corroborated by inflation_expectations (breakeven plateauing after a bounce, not accelerating) which closes the gap term_premium flagged as missing. That cross-read strengthens rather than weakens the term_premium call — inflation compensation isn't confirming higher yields, it's flat-to-soft, consistent with compression at the long end. Balance_sheet, the other flagged gap, reports flat/reinvestment-neutral with a slight downward drift in assets — not a runoff story that would push term premium up via supply pressure. So neither gap argues against the term_premium read; if anything they reinforce it.

Pulling the other way: financial_conditions shows a clean, monotonic tightening trend (NFCI at 52-week high in its range), which historically front-runs higher long-end yields via risk premia and precautionary demand for duration, but also can reflect tightening that eventually caps growth and inflation, capping yields. Labor_tightness continues to tighten (unemployment at 12-month low, no Sahm signal) — traditionally yield-supportive, but this is a 23-day-old read and the current curve/term-premium and breakeven data are fresher and directly yield-referencing. Inflation itself is judged "up" but explicitly on base effects with flat 3m annualized and pinned core PCE — weak, mechanical, not a real level driver.

