}, {"tag": "duration", "text": "NFCI tightening trend could eventually pull long yields up via risk premia even though it hasn't yet."}, {"tag": "positioning", "text": "Panel is split (financial_conditions up vs term_premium down), so level signal is weaker than usual and could reverse quickly."}], "trade": {"legs": [{"instrument": "DGS2", "weight": -0.3}, {"instrument": "DGS10", "weight": -0.4}], "conviction": 0.4, "rationale": "Modest long-duration tilt across both tenors, weighted toward the long end where term_premium and inflation_expectations evidence is freshest and most yield-direct; sized down given panel disagreement."}}

{"notes": "Since last meeting, the strongest driver of my prior short-duration position — term_premium — has flipped from "down, conviction 0.60" to "flat, conviction 0.30." The falsifier I set (sustained DGS10 rebound) has partially triggered: yields stalled and ticked up over 21d after a multi-quarter decline, though not enough to clear my 1.65-1.70% threshold. This is a real, named change in the evidence, not just a stale repeat. Balance_sheet also flipped, from "down 0.45" to "up 0.35" — the runoff/QT thesis that supported lower long-end supply pressure is gone; assets are now at the highest print in the window with positive momentum. Both of my two highest-conviction bearish-yield drivers from last time have reversed or softened materially.

Elsewhere: inflation is leaning up (0.40, core PCE firming steadily), financial_conditions and labor_tightness are flat with tight, low-volatility ranges, giving no directional push either way. Curve_slope and inflation_expectations are outside my mandate but consistent with a stabilizing rather than falling-yield backdrop.

